PUH-BrianMartell pair-instability supernovae (PISNe) produce distinctive elemental yields because the entire star is disrupted in explosive oxygen and silicon burning — no compact remnant to lock away iron-group elements. Typical yields from models (140–260 M⊙ progenitors): •  Oxygen (O, Z=8): Dominant — 50–150 M⊙ per event (often >100 M⊙ for higher masses). •  Silicon (Si, Z=14): High — 5–20 M⊙. •  Sulfur (S, Z=16): 2–10 M⊙. •  Argon/Ca (Z=18/20): 1–5 M⊙. •  Iron-group (Ni/Fe, Z=26/28): Very low — <0.1 M⊙ (almost none, unlike core-collapse SNe ~0.1 M⊙ Ni-56). Pattern: Massive even-Z α elements (O to Ca) hugely overproduced, odd-Z suppressed, iron-group nearly absent. Signature odd-even effect + high [O/Fe].
